ry works that reflected metropolitan fears of the hold that slave traders (and the slave economy more generally) had over the political, cultural, and financial networks of power. She also examines how the nineteenth-century empire and the role of the slave trader are commemorated in contemporary tourism and literature in various regions in Northern Spain. This is the first book to demonstrate the centrality of not just Cuba, but the illicit transatlantic slave trade to the cultural life of modern Spain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCollective memoryzSpainxHistoryy20th century. 0aSlave trade in literature. 0aSlave tradezSpainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlavery in literature. 0aSlaveryzCubaxHistoryy19th century. 0aSpanish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aBaroja. 4aBlanco White. 4aCuba. 4aGaldós. 4aSpain. 4acoloniality. 4aemigration. 4aempire. 4aslave trade. 4aslavery. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Spain & Portugal.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804791830zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804791830423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804791830.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles